@WenbinZhu Yes, my question is about usage of compleExceptionally(). I am saying that call compleExceptionally() does not cancel the real task. In this case, the real task is parallel read and write range.
In below test case, the real task is set flag. And it turns out that even if we call compleExceptionally() for all futures, those read and write still occurs..
@Test
    public void testCompleteExceptionally() {
        AtomicBoolean flag = new AtomicBoolean(false);
        CompletableFuture<Void> f = CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            Sleep.sleepUninterruptibly(Duration.ofSeconds(10));
            System.out.println("After 10s, set flag to true");
            flag.set(true);
        });

        Sleep.sleepUninterruptibly(Duration.ofSeconds(3));
        f.completeExceptionally(new WrongEpochException(1));

        try {
            f.join();
        } catch (CompletionException e) {
            assertThat(e).hasCauseExactlyInstanceOf(WrongEpochException.class);
        }
        System.out.println("Let's wait 10 more seconds after join");
        Sleep.sleepUninterruptibly(Duration.ofSeconds(10));
        assertThat(flag).isTrue();
    }
I am not sure keep those tasks running is good or bad. It silently transfer some batches, but I don't know how it handles exception in background.

